    <section class="consulting-more-knots" id="more-on-knots-section" aria-labelledby="more-on-knots">
      <img class="consulting-block-image consulting-block-image--crop-right" src="/assets/consulting/knot-02.png" alt="A long pine board with knots and grain flowing around them." loading="lazy">

      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 id="more-on-knots">How I think about knots</h2>

        <p>A knot begins as a branch. When a young tree is hungry, it sprouts a feeding appendage &mdash; not knowing this spot will one day cost a sawmill real money, and cost me a few nickels in steel.</p>

        <p>Each year, with the turn of the seasons, the tree lays down another ring of wood around its core, just beneath the bark. Slowly the trunk thickens around the living branch, cocooning it beneath each new layer of growth. Year after year, ring on ring.</p>

        <p>If we could watch the process sped up, the tree would look strangely animate. Bark splitting, microfissures opening new living quarters for insects that depend on these warm retreats for shelter. New wood slowly climbing over old wood. Meanwhile the buried branch keeps drinking, still carrying water up through the trunk to leaves out beyond the bark.</p>

        <p class="consulting-asterism" aria-hidden="true">* * *</p>

        <p>The tree keeps steadily growing towards the sky. But arriving at a knot on the road, the grain has to take the long way around &ndash; bending the way spacetime bends around a black hole.</p>

        <p>Around the knot, the fibers crowd together, cross paths, switch direction without warning. Sometimes the wood hardens around the knot, making your tools skate <span class="consulting-tooltip"><a class="consulting-subtle-link consulting-hover-note" data-note="no matter how sharp" tabindex="0" aria-label="uselessly &mdash; no matter how sharp">uselessly</a></span> across the surface. Sometimes the fibers tear loose all at once and leave a divot where a smooth cut was supposed to be. Wood that read clear a few inches ago suddenly makes your plane act like a shopping cart with one bad wheel.</p>

        <p>Worst case, the plane finds a knot the way a car finds a telephone pole.</p>

        <p>It&rsquo;s a bad feeling when you hit a knot.</p>

        <p>This is usually where people begin blaming their tools.</p>

        <p>You learn to read ahead a little, and this habit of reading carries over into the rest of my work.</p>

        <p class="consulting-asterism" aria-hidden="true">* * *</p>

        <p>Unfocus your mind&rsquo;s eye and a board full of knots looks like a field of galaxies.</p>

        <p>Hard problems aren&rsquo;t hard because nobody is smart enough or working hard enough. The nature of a living system is to make knots. No knots, no branches. No branches, no shade. No shade, no tree to fall asleep against.</p>

        <p>The grain starts moving in several directions at once.</p>

        <p>My work is to read the grain, describe the knot, and find the next cut.</p>

        <p class="consulting-end-ornament" aria-hidden="true">&#10086;</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-more-knots" id="common-knots-section" aria-labelledby="common-knots">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 id="common-knots">Common knots and useful tools</h2>

        <p class="consulting-subhead" id="wicked-problems-subhead">The problem with wicked problems</p>

        <p>&ldquo;Wicked problems&rdquo; is a frame for hard problems. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/14494035.2019.1617971">The term has been used too many ways to mean much.</a> Once I&rsquo;ve called something wicked, I know it&rsquo;s hard. I don&rsquo;t know what kind of hard, or what to do next.</p>

        <p>We need a better diagnostic concept for knots. I prefer <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volatility,_uncertainty,_complexity_and_ambiguity">VUCA</a>. VUCA problems are characterized by four things:</p>

        <p><strong>Volatility</strong> &ndash; frequent change; unstable conditions.</p>

        <p><strong>Uncertainty</strong> &ndash; lack of predictability; prospect of surprise.</p>

        <p><strong>Complexity</strong> &ndash; many confounding forces; no clear cause and effect.</p>

        <p><strong>Ambiguity</strong> &ndash; haziness of reality; mixed meanings of conditions.</p>

        <p>Each can be diagnosed and addressed separately, unlike wicked problems, which treat difficulty as a single category.</p>

        <p>Most real work worth doing has at least two of these going at once, and a lot of what I do is figuring out which tools fit the knot in front of us.</p>

        <p class="consulting-subhead" id="commonly-encountered-knots">Commonly encountered knots and example tools</p>

        <p><strong>Volatility</strong> &ndash; short feedback loops; willingness to be wrong on a known schedule.</p>

        <p><strong>Uncertainty</strong> &ndash; naming what we don&rsquo;t know; sketching scenarios explicitly.</p>

        <p><strong>Complexity</strong> &ndash; mapping the parts before pulling on any; finding the rate-limiting variable.</p>

        <p><strong>Ambiguity</strong> &ndash; working the question, not the answer; restating from each stakeholder&rsquo;s frame.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
